{{About|a scholarly journal|the subject|American diplomacy}} {{Infobox journal | title = American Diplomacy | cover = | discipline = [[Diplomacy]] | abbreviation = Am. Dipl. | editor = Beatrice Camp (as from March 2018) | publisher = American Diplomacy Publishers | country = United States | history = 1996–present | frequency = Upon acceptance | openaccess = Yes | website = http://www.unc.edu/depts/diplomat/ | link1 = http://www.unc.edu/depts/diplomat/static/archives.html | link1-name = Online archive | eISSN = 1094-8120 | OCLC = 37358956 | LCCN = sn97004360 }} '''''American Diplomacy''''' is an [[open access]] [[peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] published by the [[nonprofit]] American Diplomacy Publishers in cooperation with the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] College of Arts and Sciences's Curriculum in Peace, War and Defense, and with the consortium Triangle Institute for Security Studies, one of the wave of Grand Strategy programs, a group of academic-military, pro-interventionist organizations that developed after 9/11. It covers the [[foreign policy of the United States]] and its [[United States Foreign Service|foreign service]], and states it maintains a partisan political stance.<ref name="pubPolicies">{{cite web |url=http://www.unc.edu/depts/diplomat/static/edpub_policies.html |title=Editorial and Publication Policies |publisher=American Diplomacy Publishers |accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref> It publishes analytical commentary and analysis on [[international relations]], notes on life in the foreign service, [[book review]]s, and editorials.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unc.edu/depts/diplomat/static/about.html |title=About American Diplomacy |publisher=American Diplomacy Publishers |accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref>
