'''William Ferguson Massey''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|PC|size=85%}} (26 March 1856 – 10 May 1925), commonly known as '''Bill Massey''', was an Irish-born politician in New Zealand who served as the [[List of Prime Ministers of New Zealand|19th Prime Minister of New Zealand]] from  May 1912 to May 1925. He was the founding leader of the  [[New Zealand Reform Party|Reform Party]], New Zealand's second organised political party, from 1909 until his death.

Massey was born in [[County Londonderry]] in Ireland. After migrating to New Zealand in 1870, Massey farmed near [[Auckland]] (earning his later nickname, ''Farmer Bill'') and assumed leadership in farmers' organisations. He entered parliament in 1894 as a [[historic conservatism in New Zealand|conservative]], and from 1894 to 1912 was a leader of the conservative opposition to the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal]] ministries of [[Richard Seddon]] and [[Joseph Ward]]. Massey became the first Reform Party Prime Minister following Ward's resignation in March 1912. Throughout his political career Massey was known for the particular support he showed for [[agrarianism|agrarian]] interests, as well as his opposition to [[organised labour]]. He pledged New Zealand's support for Britain during the [[First World War]]. 

Massey led his Reform Party through four elections, although only the [[New Zealand general election, 1919|1919 election]] was a decisive victory over all other parties. After Richard Seddon, he is the second-[[List of Prime Ministers of New Zealand by term|longest-serving]] Prime Minister of New Zealand.

==Early life==
Massey was born in 1856 into a Protestant farming family, and grew up in [[Limavady]], [[County Londonderry]] in Ireland. His father John Massey and his mother Marianne (or Mary Anne) née Ferguson were tenant farmers, who also owned a small property. His family arrived in New Zealand on 21 October 1862 on board the ''Indian Empire''<ref>{{cite news |title=Port of Onehunga |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=DSC18621021.2.3.2 |newspaper=[[Daily Southern Cross]] |volume=XVIII |issue=1638 |date=21 October 1862 |page=2}}</ref> as Nonconformist settlers,<ref>1911 Encyclopædia Britannica</ref> although Massey remained in Ireland for a further eight years to complete his education. After arriving on 10 December 1870 on the ''City of Auckland'', Massey worked as a farmhand for some years before acquiring his own farm in Mangere, south Auckland, in 1876.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/article.jsp?articleid=34921&back=&version=2006-10 |title=Oxford DNB |publisher=Oxford DNB |date=1925-05-10 |accessdate=2016-03-29}}</ref> In 1882 Massey married his neighbour's daughter, [[Christina Allan Massey|Christina Allan Paul]]. They had seven children.<ref name="DNZB Massey">{{DNZB|Gustafson|Barry|2m39|Massey, William Ferguson|10 December 2011||Barry Gustafson}}</ref>

==Early political career==
Massey gradually became more prominent in his community. This was partly due to his civic involvement in the school board, the debating society,<!-- [[freemasonry]] and the [[Orange Order]], ANY PROOF?? -->and farming associations. Because of his prominence in these circles, he became involved in political debate, working on behalf of rural conservatives against the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] government of [[John Ballance]]. {{Citation needed|date=December 2010}} William Massey was a member of the [[Orange Order]], [[Oddfellows]], and [[freemasons]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/2m39/massey-william-ferguson |title=Massey, William Ferguson – Biography – Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand |website=Teara.govt.nz |date= |accessdate=2016-03-29}}</ref> and espoused [[British Israelism|British Israelite]] ideas.<ref>
