Massey joined the ranks of the (mostly conservative) independent MPs opposing the Liberal Party, led by [[Richard Seddon]]. They were poorly organised and dispirited, and had little chance of unseating the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberals]]. [[William Russell (New Zealand politician)|William Russell]], the [[Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Leader of the Opposition]], was able to command only 15 votes. Massey brought increased vigour to the conservative faction.

While the conservatives rallied for a time, support for the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberals]] increased markedly during the [[Second Boer War]], leaving the conservatives devastated. Massey's political career survived the period: despite a challenge by [[William Herries]], he remained the most prominent opponent to the Liberal Party.

After Seddon's death the Liberals were led by [[Joseph Ward]], who proved more vulnerable to Massey's attacks. In particular, Massey made gains by claiming that alleged corruption and cronyism within the civil service was ignored or abetted by the Liberal government. His conservative politics also benefited him when voters grew concerned about militant [[trade union|unionism]] and the supposed threat of socialism.

===Reform Party===

In February 1909,<ref>{{cite news |title=The Reform Party |url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=EP19090212.2.97 |accessdate=23 March 2016 |work=[[The Evening Post (New Zealand)|The Evening Post]] |volume=LXVVII |issue=36 |date=12 February 1909 |page=8}}</ref> Massey announced the creation of the [[New Zealand Reform Party|Reform Party]] from his New Zealand Political Reform League. The party was to be led by him and backed by his conservative colleagues.

In the [[New Zealand general election, 1911|1911 election]] the Reform Party won more seats than the Liberal Party but did not gain an absolute majority. The Liberals, relying on support from independents who had not joined Reform, were able to stay in power until the following year, when they lost a vote of confidence.

==Prime Minister==
Massey was sworn in as [[Prime Minister of New Zealand|Prime Minister]] on 10 July 1912. Two days later it was reported in the press on 12 July that he had accepted the appointment of Honorary Commandant of the Auckland District of the Legion of Frontiersmen. Some members of the Reform Party grew increasingly frustrated at Massey's dominance of the party. He earned the enmity of many workers with his harsh response to [[Waihi miners' strike|miners']] and [[1913 Great Strike|waterfront workers' strikes]] in 1912 and 1913. The use of force to deal with the strikers made Massey an object of hatred for the emerging left-wing, but conservatives (many of whom believed that the unions were controlled by the far left) generally supported him, saying that his methods were necessary. His association with the Legion of Frontiersmen assisted him greatly during this period as a number of mounted units, including Levin Troop, rode to Wellington in mufti and assisted as Special Constables. In the Levin Troop was a young [[Bernard Freyberg]], who would shortly earn the Victoria Cross near Beaumont Hamel.

Amongst the first Acts enacted by Massey's government was one that "enabled some 13,000 Crown tenants to purchase their own farms."<ref name="UCred">{{Citation |last=Allen |first=Sam |title=To Ulster's Credit |year=1985 |page=116 |location=Killinchy, UK }}</ref>

===First World War===
{{Cquote|All we are and all we have is at the disposal of the British Government.|20px|20px|Cable from Massey to the British Government, 1914<ref name="UCred"/>}}
The outbreak of the [[First World War]] diverted attention from these matters. The [[New Zealand general election, 1914|1914 election]] left Massey and his political opponents stalemated in parliament, with neither side possessing enough support to govern effectively. Massey reluctantly invited [[Joseph Ward]] of the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberals]] to form a war-time coalition, created in 1915. While Massey remained Prime Minister, Ward gained de facto status as joint leader. Massey and Ward travelled to Britain several times, both during and after the war, to discuss military co-operation and peace settlements. During his first visit, Massey visited New Zealand troops, listening to their complaints sympathetically. This angered some officials, who believed that Massey undermined the military leadership by conceding (in contrast to the official line) that conditions for the troops were unsatisfactory. The war reinforced Massey's strong belief in the British Empire and New Zealand's links with it. He attended the Peace Conference in 1919 and signed the [[Treaty of Versailles]] on behalf of  New Zealand.  Although turning down knighthoods and a peerage, he accepted appointment as a Grand Officer of the [[Order of the Crown (Belgium)]] from the King of Belgium in March 1921 and a Grand Officer of the [[Legion of Honour]] by the President of France in October 1921.<ref>M. Brewer, 'New Zealand and the Légion d'honneur: Officiers, Commandeurs and Dignites', The Volunteers: The Journal of the New Zealand Military Historical Society, 35(3), March 2010, p.136.</ref>

====Coalition with the Liberals====
[[File:NZ Prime Minister William Massey addressing New Zealand machine gunners at Bois-De-Warnimont, France, June 1918 (16650304790).jpg|thumb|Massey addressing New Zealand machine gunners at Bois-De-Warnimont, France, 30 June 1918]]
[[File:Massey and Ward.jpg|thumb|Massey and Ward, {{circa|1920}}]]
Partly because of the difficulty in obtaining consensus to implement meaningful policies, the coalition government had grown increasingly unpopular by the end of the war. Massey was particularly worried by the rise of the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]], which was growing increasingly influential. Massey also found himself fighting off criticism from within his own party, including charges that he was ignoring rural concerns. He dissolved the coalition in 1919, and fought both the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberals]] and [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour]] on a platform of patriotism, stability, support for farmers, and a public works program. He successfully gained a majority.

===The Red Scare===

According to New Zealand historian Tony Wilson, Massey was known for his anti-[[Bolshevik]] and anti-Soviet sentiments. He disliked domestic socialist elements like the "Red Feds", the predecessor to the [[New Zealand Council of Trade Unions|New Zealand Federation of Labour]], and the [[New Zealand Labour Party]].  As Prime Minister, Massey was opposed to Communist influence. He regarded the [[Red Terror]] (1919–20) in the [[Soviet Union]], which followed the [[Bolshevik Revolution]] in 1917, as proof of the "inherently oppressive orientation" of socialism. In response to the Red Scare the government passed the War Regulations Continuance Act, which continued wartime emergency regulations including censorship. This led to a ban on Communist-oriented literature, which continued to 1935.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wilson |first=Tony|editor-first=Alexander |editor-last=Trapeznik |title=Lenin's Legacy Down Under |publisher=Otago University Press|year=2004|pages=101–02 |chapter=Chapter 6: Defining the Red Menace|isbn=1-877276-90-1}}</ref>

===1922 election===

Economic problems lessened support for Reform. In the [[New Zealand general election, 1922|1922 election]] Massey lost his majority, and was forced to negotiate with independents to keep his government alive. He was also alarmed by the success of Labour, which was now only five seats behind the Liberals. He began to believe that the Liberals would eventually disappear, with their supporters being split, the socially liberal wing to Labour and the economically liberal wing to Reform. He set about trying to ensure that Reform's gain would be the greater.

In 1924 cancer forced him to relinquish many of his official duties, and the following year he died. The [[Massey Memorial]] was erected as his [[mausoleum]] in Wellington, paid for mostly by public subscription. [[Massey University]] is named after him, the name chosen because the university had a focus on [[agricultural science]], matching Massey's own farming background.

==Honours==
* {{Flag|France}}: [[Image:Legion Honneur GO ribbon.svg|80px]] [[Grand Officer]] of the [[Legion of Honour]]
* {{Flag|Belgium}}: [[Grand Officer]] of the [[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|Order of the Crown]]

==Family==
His widow, [[Christina Allan Massey|Christina]], was awarded the [[Order of the British Empire|GBE]] in 1926, one year after his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/overview/history.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=20 May 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110804214234/http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/overview/history.html |archivedate=4 August 2011 }}</ref>

Two of his sons became Reform MPs: [[Jack Massey (politician)|Jack]] (1885–1964), who represented his father's [[Franklin (New Zealand electorate)|Franklin electorate]] from 1928 to 1935, and from 1938 to 1957 for National; and [[Walter William Massey|Walter William]] (1882–1959), who represented [[Hauraki (New Zealand electorate)|Hauraki]] from 1931 to 1935.

